POLICE are now deploying senior officers at all roadblocks and security checkpoints as the law enforcement agency moves to tighten screws in the fight against public indiscipline during this Covid-19 lockdown.
In a memorandum to district police commanders, the force expressed concern over the continued violations of lockdown regulations by nonessential service businesses as well as individuals in the capital. National police spokesperson Paul Nyathi yesterday confirmed the memorandum, but insisted it was meant to be internal. “The Zimbabwe Republic Police (ZRP) has taken note of a leaked memorandum from officer commanding Harare province to officer commanding districts on Covid-19 regulations enforcement. “The public should take note that this was an internal communication to guide commanders on the implementation of Statutory Instrument 10/2021 which amended the principal order Statutory instrument 200/2020. In the memorandum, senior officers are now expected to take charge of security checkpoints as the force tightens the movement of people without valid lockdown exemption letters. “An inspector should be deployed at busy roadblocks in big cities so that correct decisions are made. At other checkpoints, a sergeant or assistant inspector should be in charge depending on the level of activities at that particular point. “It has been noted that some individuals and businesses are now operating in violation of Statutory Instrument 10 of 2021 which barred all non-essential service providers to operate during the current…. national lockdown. “Companies and businesses not in that category but operating should close. This is regardless of being in possession of exemption letters,” the memorandum read. Meanwhile, the police have arrested four suspects for allegedly possessing and vandalising copper cables in Hatfield and Southlea Park in Harare. “In another case which occurred on January 27, 2021 at around 1900hrs at the Ushewekunze turnoff, Harare, along Harare-Masvingo road, two suspects Norest Tanyaradzwa ,27, and Lindon Chikura,38 , were intercepted while transporting 260 metres of armoured cables and 2 000 metres aluminium cables…destined for smuggling through Beitbridge Border Post,” Nyathi said. Sponsored Links

    
      
        
          
